  "lesson_id": "lesson_conjugation_mizenkei",
  "lesson_title": "The 'Unrealized' Base: Introduction to Mizenkei (未然形)",
  "lesson_summary": "In this lesson, we introduce the Mizenkei (未然形), a specific verb form used for actions that have not yet occurred, such as negation ('not doing') or volition ('will do').",
  "grammar_point": "conjugation_mizenkei",
  "grammar_explanation": {
    "concept": "In Classical Japanese, verbs change their ending (conjugate) depending on what follows them. The Mizenkei (未然形) is the 'Unrealized Base.' The name comes from the Kanji 未 (not yet) and 然 (so/happened). It acts as a logic gate: if you want to attach a word meaning 'not' or 'will,' the verb must first switch into this 'pending' state.",
    "formation": "For many verbs, the Mizenkei is formed by changing the final vowel to an 'a' sound (e.g., 'aw-u' becomes 'aw-a'). For irregular verbs like 'to come' (kuru), it changes to 'ko'.",
    "variations": [
      "Used with 'zu' or 'de' for negation (Not doing)",
      "Used with 'mu' for volition or future intent (Will do)"
    ],
    "common_confusions": [
      "Do not confuse with the Rentaikei (Unit 3), which is used to modify nouns. Mizenkei cannot stand alone or modify nouns; it only exists to 'glue' to specific auxiliaries."
    ]
  },
  "teaching_sequence": [
    {
      "type": "introduction",
      "content": "You have already mastered how to link nouns with particles and how to use the Rentaikei to describe things. Now, we move into the realm of the 'Unrealized.' In Chinese, you might use '不' (bù) or '将' (jiāng) before a verb. In Classical Japanese, the verb itself must transform into the **Mizenkei (未然形)** before these logical modifiers can be attached. Think of it as a 'pre-execution' state in programming."
    },
